column38:
Fuji started the race last in the pace pack, but quickly overtook to lead the pace pack by the start of position keeping. Lone Wolf did not proc, so neither did groundwork. She held that position for most of mid race, barring losing it once, only to get it back with a proc of It's On! She didn't get any acceleration procs, but she procced Speed Star just before the last spurt for carryover speed. Immediately upon hitting the final straight, she procced Lights of Vaudeville and pace straightaways. That, in addition to soundly winning a duel with the 2nd place Taiki, placed her in 1st by 2.5 lengths. 

I made her the day before with a deck of MLB Kitasan spd, MLB sTosho spd, MLB Bakushin Speed, MLB Urara guts, 1LB Riko SSR, and borrowing MLB Fine Motion Wit. Did a few extra races for skill points, and got lucky with a golden inspiration giving lots of hints.

column9: I never use my R Riko
column38:
The race was looking extremely rough; the mayano and taiki had really solid stats, and really good skills. The Oonige suzuka wasn't necessarily a problem, but if my Scarlet didn't try to overtake at the right time, she would be cooked and not be able to win at all. The other late surgers all had much higher power than mine, as well as both red shift and pump, meaning that it was super unlikely that my late surgers are able to contest.

The race started as expected, with my late surgers in the far back, and scarlet a little behind suzuka, and it stayed like that till the late race. As we were coming into the final corner, I see Scarlet fall back instead of push up, and immediately I realize that I'm screwed. Taiki and Mayano are pushing up super hard, and there's no way for Scarlet to get the rod if she's this far back, this late into the race. 

Then, as soon as it's too late, Scarlet pops her ult, and she stays in front of the pace chasers and is suddenly gaining on the suzuka. But the camera POV has already shifted, and the corner was already passed by the time she got neck and neck with her. Then, as they enter the straight, I see Angling and Scheming proc, and she rockets ahead, with the pace chasers already on her ass, but they never manage to gain on her. They have more speed, more power, and proc'd their accels at the perfect time, but Scarlet never lets them overtake, and its a dub for little miss perfect. Everything I know about this game, and the evidence from the past few days of this CM, tells me that she should've lost as soon as she fell back on the late race, but she just decided not to. First time building a front runner, and I think I'll only ever build Scarlet as one. No other frontrunner is this hype.

column38:
Me:
[2nd] Late - Vodka (23/80 Wins)
[4th] Late - Grass Wonder (11/80 Wins)
[9th] Late - Mejiro Ryan (14/80 Wins)

Opponent 1:
[5th] Runaway - Suzuka (10/60 Wins)
[1st] Front - Summer Maruzensky (4/60 Wins)
[8th] Pace - Oguri Cap (13/60 Wins)

Opponent 2:
[6th] Pace - Oguri Cap (9/65 Wins)
[7th] Late - Vodka (4/80 Wins)
[3rd] Late - Mejiro Ryan (18/80)

The winner had a Runaway Suzuka that was an ace. It made a huge gap and naturally the fronts and pacers pulled away from the lates because of it.

My Grass late started. I had 5th/6th locked down with Vodka/Ryan. 
Then on the very last moment before final leg, 3rd player's Ryan took 6th from mine and got pump.

My Vodka triggered Slick Surge and Pump soon after. 
Grass got Updrafters. 
Ryan got Slick Surge and but swung extremely wide on her own, everyone else inner lanes.

Opponent 1's Runaway Suzuka took Angling, but immediately fell back into Maru's path and she got NSM proc and that was game.

My Vodka did enough to overcome the Ryan's Pump and beat her, but no chance was she stopping a Maru who NSM'ed from a Runaway.

My Vodka has 1200+S/634/1177/421/480, 2x Right-Handed, 1x Fall Runner and finished 3/4L behind. She lost to this 4/60 winrate gamble.

I was out gamba'd.

column40:
1. Win Rates need to be segregated per Uma for the initial rounds. Maybe you can add a "how many races did Uma 1 win option next to the Uma and her style selection.
2. Some people change Umas midway through rounds; so there needs to be an option to select more than 3 Umas for a particular round.
3. [If possible] Add an (optional) skill chart for Umas that people select for the rounds form (similar to how people would select skills for the umalator sim). That way, y'all can have more data to show which skills correspond to higher win rates [And how many BOFA demons there are] - maybe similar to the experimental OCR you're using right now.
4. Just like the support cards in this form, ask if people own the meta Umas. How many people own Taiki but did not use her. Something like that to differentiate people who don't have the meta Uma from those that do but do not want to use her. Idk, I think it'd be fun to visualise that data tbh.
5. Moomoocows should advertise it more. Shill for it in other communities - collab with other content creators, or at least ask them to advertise the form at least if possible - so that their viewers can hear about this and enter their data. The more data, the better it is to minimise outliers and randomness. 
6. I realise that I'm in the minority here, but google forms are really annoying for me because I do not use a google account at all. Therefore, the form having a mandatory sign in is cumbersome. But I do understand that you want to dissuade trolls from entering random data that an anonymous form would allow, and also to have form progress be saved after each day, so I'm not sure what the correct way to do it would be either. It's just annoying, but I get your position, so it's all g.
7. Most importantly, thank you for all the work you all put in :)

Gold City saved the day... but stole the win from my oshi. FML

column40: New question: "Estimate the total number of support card pulls you have done, to the nearest hundred."  The point is that whaling causes, and having high LB SSR cards is the result of, pulling a lot from the support card banner.  It should also be a somewhat reliable measure of account strength as it is a decent estimator of how good a player's deck of SR cards is as well.  Also, there are regression techniques that can be used to see whether having a high level SSR card is actually predictive of performance or more just a side effect of having a generally strong stack of support cards (e.g., whales might have a lot of Biko Pegasus SSRs and that might result in Biko Pegasus SSR looking stronger than in reality.)  If you have any questions I'm CatDrugs on the discord and I'd be happy to help with the analyses.

column38: My lobby had 1 front (my Summer Maru), 7 late surgers, and 1 end closer. (Un)fortunately, there was no Taiki Shuttle in my lobby. When the race started, my Vodka only got the late start. Until, I saw my late surgers Digital and Vodka not in 6th place, I knew they won't be proc-ing Let's Pump Some Iron. I saw first enemy team's Oguri Cap in 6th, zooming in by proc-ing Pump, and I knew the match is over. Digitan did what she could do to get at least 2nd place but NARITA TAISHIN of the second enemy team approached crazy and outmaneuvered my Digitan and placed 2nd with a head length. column38:
I lucked out a bit with my finals lobby. The guy who finished 3rd place re-used their Maruzensky (regular, not summer) from Leo cup (not Cancer, it had medium S and 900+ stam) that did not have groundwork or rod. They had a solid Vodka and good Taiki, but neither was optimized well with their skills. The guy who finished 2nd had very good umas - mile S on all 3 and uma stan on Curren/Taiki with superstan on Digitan. But same story with their skills. The only accels on the entire team were iron on Digitan, Curren/Taiki's own uniques, and ignited PWR on Curren.
For the race - it came down to the 3 Taikis at the very end. My Taiki was in 6th place with ~600m to go. She passed one Taiki to get to 5th and activated It's On! and SFV at the same time as they were rounding the corner. She got to 1st place by the time the corner was done, activated straight descent and head-on at the same time, and ended up beating the 2nd place Taiki by a head. 3rd place Taiki finished 3/4 L behind them, with my Taishin and then the Digitan neck and neck.
My Taiki was really good in round 1, I think she had 10 of my 18 wins across the 2 days. But she struggled a lot in round 2 and only picked up 3 wins in those 2 days, often coming in 2nd or 3rd place to better Taikis with mile S and similar skills. I was expecting the same in this race since she was stuck in 6th place until the last corner, but it seemed like absolute perfect activation for all of her late race skills to get me the win. Taishin was my MVP of the CM because of her round 2 wins, but she couldn't get good activation timing on nemesis/iron/red shift with 6 front/pace umas in the lobby. She still finished 4th anyway. We don't talk about my Falcon, she tried her best.
column40:
Only things I can think of are individual uma win rates for each day/round, and something like tracking team composition day to day or round to round to see if/how people change strategies. For example, In R1D1 I used Falcon-Taiki-Taishin and did well enough. I used R1D2 to try out Taiki-Grass-Taishin and gamble more, but did worse overall and noticed that Taiki was losing to fronts more often. I figured that even when she wasn't winning, Falcon was effectively working as a blocker for non-runaway Suzuka fronts which made it easier for Taiki/Taishin to catch up and pass them. 
You guys do an awesome job and it's already much improved from the first form. This stuff just makes the CMs more fun.

column38:
Vodka procced straightaway adept early, 2 more white speed skills mid game and went far ahead of the late surger packs but still placed 6 because there was a lot of pace chasers which allowed her to move up to 5th and triggered red shift right before final corner. Vodka procced her ult followed by 1,500,000 CC and overtook Seiun Sky right before the finish line by a head length.

Additional Note:
- Vodka was the only one with Mile S in that lobby. The rest of the aces had max speed except for one Taiki Shuttle with 1195 speed and the Nice Nature with 1141 speed.
- The 2nd place Seiun Sky had 1000 power, only 500 wit and uses 2LB SSR tazuna + MLB SSR riko
- 3rd place by 1 3/4 length was an A+ Oguri Cap, 4th place by 1/2 length was an S rank Taiki Shuttle with 30% winrate.

column38: My Vodka and Ryan were both parent runs. I was too focused on getting a good Taiki with Mile S and only managed to do that the day Virgo M started. Since I didn't want to keep training for Virgo, I used my best Vodka and Ryan and they both did good enough. Vodka won 9 out of 81 races. None of my Uma's activated their Ult's in the finale. Vodka was 4. fav, Taiki 3. Fav and Ryan 2. Fav. Vodka and Ryan were both rushed during the Finale. My Taiki went first at the end of the second half, overtaking Bourbon who was in 1st place from the start. Vodka on 6. and Ryan on 7. place at the time. The other Taiki actived her Ult but my Vodka made her way into 2. place and my Ryan into 3. place, both only with Late Surger Corners. No one in the Lobby used Let's Pump Some Iron! My three Aces had to duel against each other, all in the first three places. Right behind them were Bourbon who activated her Ult and Fuji. The other Vodka tried to catch up with her Ult while my Ryan activated NSM. My three aces were a good bit in front of the others when my Vodka activated Mile Straightaways, pushing her even further ahead and help her win! Ryan came in 2nd with 1/2 L and Taiki in 3rd with 3/4 L. Sorry for the book, but I am so happy. My first CM Win!

column38:
Let me start with saying that I put my finals into practice mode and I won 10 races out of 10.  Starting was fine, enemy S.Maru had no groundwork, so my Seiun and Maru were fighting eachother, after 1 early spot struggle, Seiun got absolutely demolished, despite activating 5 skills, she couldn't contest my Maru (4 skill activation before her ult). Despite Seiun Sky activating 5 skills and the winning Oguri activating 1 skill, she quickly caught up to the enemy Maru and my Seiun. Right before accel zone, Oguri activated Speed Star, carrying her speed, then she got blocked by my Seiun Sky right when accel zone started, activating No Stopping Me. Slightly after, the 6th placed Vodka who activated pump also got stuck on my Seiun Sky, activating No Stopping Me too. My Summer Maru who got no competition this race got absolutely demolished with her 0.2 accel vs enemy 0.4 accels. 
The guy who won only had no stopping me, angling and scheming on Maru and red shift on Vodka, no other viable accel skills. No pump, no head-on, no straight descent,  no groundwork or early lead on S.Maru. My umas are superior in every way, my Vodka is the best out of all of them, I won the race 10 times out of 11, Cygames just happened to rig the finals.

column38:
Got lucky, what can I say, even with less than a week of team building you can win. The winner uma, my seiun doesn't have good stats but have incredible skills. Because the good early race skills like groundwork, focus, early lead, and prudent + dodging danger, she almost never lose to other front runners except runaway suzuka. Even then with the midrace skills, my seiun can catch up to runaways and take the rod. Unfortunately due to bad speed and power, she will most likely lose to backliners even after rod.

My lobby in the finals Is definitely not ordinary, here is the list : 
Opponent's suzuka was not a runaway and no groundwork, 
S Maru have groundwork but can't proc it, 
Oguri cap only have 3 recovery skills and 1 speed skill (rudolf's unique), 
digital have poor speed stat around 1000, 
taiki is below average stats but do have some good skills, 
opponent's vodka having slick surge as the only accel.

The race starts normally, seiun took the lead because of the skills. Mid race skills made her able to keep the 1st position until late race and activate the unique. My vodka and rice shower somehow missed every accel. I thought I will lose to the taiki, but turns out she don't have enough stat or skills to catch up with seiun.

column38:
Honestly I got pretty lucky with an easy lobby that didn't have any strong opponents.

Brian got stuck on the inner lane so her unique never procced, but OYL and updrafters both procced correctly thst allowed her to break through the inner lane anyways to win.

Curren got second so she would have won even if Brian didn't proc her accels. Using opposing Suzuka as a stepping stone for her unique has been very powerful this CM, and it happened in the finals too.

Brian took about 30 runs to accomplish due to the difficulty of hitting stat benchmarks while having enough stamina to get first in spring tenno sho. She's very strong in theory but in practice that one race means her stats suffer abit due to the need to emphasise stamina and guts early on, so when I got this Brian I ended my ace runs despite no max speed.

In contrast, Curren took just 3 runs.

Recording of finals if you are very free(probably not): https://youtu.be/tlS-EMeZWes

column38:
Lobby only had my 2 fronts, who got off TTL and groundwork to build a strong lead. My Taiki had a late start, but the only other pace was a 480 wit Oguri so she caught up very quickly. The fronts spot struggled to further build the lead and my Taiki quickly followed behind with skill procs and wit pace up checks.
At the race's 2/3 mark, my Taiki was in third with about 8 lengths on the fourth place. Scarlet won the front battle to proc angling and Taiki procs SFV with speed carry over just before passing Seiun Sky.
Mejiro Ryan procs Let's Pump Some Iron but she's far back and only has 1119 speed, she can't catch up.
Scarlet procs a slightly late unique and fights Taiki for first, but Taiki won in the end by by 1 and 3/4 lengths.

This race showed off the strength of my Taiki's 1147 wit and 2k skill points, pushing up to the strong fronts even before the late race.
